r 1931 military strike leading to a takeover of the Northeast, the Chinese responded in three major ways: collaboration, resistance in exile, and resistance on the ground. What motives prompted some Chinese to collaborate, others to resist? What were conditions like under the Japanese? Through careful reading of Chinese and Japanese sources, particularly local government records, newspapers, and journals published both inside and outside occupied Manchuria, Mitter sheds important new light on these questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNationalismzChinazManchuria. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  achina.  achinese history.  achinese nationalism.  acollaborators.  acolonialism.  aexile.  agovernment.  ahistory.  aimperialism.  ajapan.  ajapanese occupation.  akwantung army.  aleague of nations.  ama zhanshan.  amanchukuo.  amanchuria.  amay thirtieth incident.  amilitary.  ananjing.  anation.  anationalism.  anonfiction.  aoccupied zone.  apolitical history.  apolitics.  apostwar.  apuppet government.  arebellion.  aresistance fighters.  aresistance.  asalvation society.  atanggu truce.  aversailles conference.  aviolence.  awar.  azhang xueliang.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022111640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092388140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923881/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY